---
title: Nx vs moon
description: Nx vs moon (moonrepo) on task running, remote caching, CI distribution, code generation, and ecosystem. moon pairs a Rust task runner with toolchain management; Nx adds graph-aware plugins, zero-config remote caching, and a CI platform.
filter: 'type:Guides'
sidebar:
  label: Nx vs moon
---

moon and Nx cover the same core loop: task running, caching, and affected detection. Nx adds the platform around it, managed remote caching, CI distribution, a plugin ecosystem, and release tooling, that moon leaves to you or doesn't offer.

## What is Nx?

Nx is a build system that orchestrates the tools you already use. Plugins configure tasks from your existing configs, caching works locally and remotely, `nx affected` runs only what your change touches, and Nx Cloud distributes tasks across CI machines. It spans JS/TS, JVM, .NET, and more in one graph.

## What is moon?

moon is a Rust-based monorepo task runner paired with [proto](https://moonrepo.dev/proto), a toolchain version manager. It runs tasks from a project graph with local caching, affected detection, and static CI sharding, and is maintained as an MIT open-source project.

## Quick takeaway

The core loop is close: both run tasks from a project graph, cache by hashing inputs, and detect affected projects. moon's standout is proto, pinned toolchains that Nx doesn't try to manage. The gap is the platform. Nx has managed remote caching with a free tier, CI distribution and test splitting, a framework plugin ecosystem, code generation, and release management. moon offers static CI sharding, a bring-your-own remote cache, and no framework plugins. Both are honest polyglot contenders, so the decision is how much of that platform you want to run yourself.

| Topic                                                             | Nx                                                       | moon                                                     |
| ----------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------- |
| [Toolchain management](#toolchain-management)                     | Not provided, composes with mise, volta, or proto itself | proto pins and auto-downloads Node, Go, Rust, Python     |
| [Task configuration](#task-configuration)                         | Auto-configured by plugins from tool configs             | Explicit, config-driven with task inheritance            |
| [Remote caching](#remote-caching)                                 | Nx Cloud, zero-config with a free tier                   | Bring your own Bazel REAPI endpoint                      |
| [CI distribution](#ci-distribution)                               | Nx Agents, Atomizer, flaky re-runs, self-healing CI      | Static sharding via `--job` / `--job-total`              |
| [Polyglot support](#polyglot-support)                             | Graph-aware plugins parse Gradle, MSBuild, imports       | Generic process running + WASM toolchains (JS, Rust, Go) |
| [Code generation and migrations](#code-generation-and-migrations) | AST-aware generators, automated dependency migrations    | Template scaffolding, no update automation               |
| [Module boundaries](#module-boundaries)                           | Import-analysis lint rule, tags, conformance rules       | Layer and tag constraints in workspace config            |
| [Ecosystem](#ecosystem)                                           | Framework plugins, Nx Console, large community           | Small, two-maintainer open source project                |

## Toolchain management

This is moon's standout feature, and Nx has no equivalent. proto pins tool versions in `.prototools`, auto-downloads them, and moon runs each task with the exact declared toolchain, so a fresh clone or CI machine needs no setup-node step. If reproducible toolchains across dev and CI are a top priority, moon owns this layer.

Nx composes with existing version managers instead of replacing them, including proto itself: nothing stops you from using proto for versions and Nx for everything below.

## Task configuration

moon is explicit by design: tasks, inputs, and outputs are declared in `moon.yml` and inherited through workspace-level task files scoped by toolchain, layer, or tag. The inheritance model keeps large workspaces consistent, at the cost of maintaining those contracts by hand.

Nx [configures tasks from the tools themselves](/docs/concepts/inferred-tasks): `@nx/vite` reads `vite.config.ts`, `@nx/gradle` reads your Gradle build, and cache inputs and outputs come from the tool's own configuration. Both models support explicit overrides. They differ in what the default requires of you. Nx also maintains workspace housekeeping like TypeScript project references through [sync generators](/docs/concepts/sync-generators), and generates CODEOWNERS from project-level [owners](/docs/enterprise/owners).

## Remote caching

moon's hosted cache service, moonbase, was sunset in March 2025. Remote caching now means bringing your own Bazel Remote Execution API endpoint: a self-hosted `bazel-remote` instance or a third-party cache service, which you operate, secure, and pay for separately. moon's docs note its TLS/mTLS support is unstable.

[Nx Replay](/docs/features/ci-features/remote-cache) is zero-config: connect a workspace to Nx Cloud, which has a free tier, and every developer and CI machine shares a managed cache with [access control and branch-scoped isolation](/docs/concepts/ci-concepts/cache-security) built in.

## CI distribution

moon's CI story is `moon ci` with static sharding: `--job N --job-total M` slices the task graph across a fixed set of jobs you provision. There is no dynamic balancing, no test splitting, and flaky handling is a static per-task `retryCount`.

[Nx Agents](/docs/features/ci-features/distribute-task-execution) allocate tasks to machines continuously based on historical timings, [Atomizer](/docs/features/ci-features/split-e2e-tasks) splits e2e suites into distributable per-file tasks, [flaky task detection](/docs/features/ci-features/flaky-tasks) identifies and retries nondeterministic tasks automatically, and [self-healing CI](/docs/features/ci-features/self-healing-ci) proposes verified fixes. Both tools ship an MCP server for local AI agents. The CI-side AI capabilities are Nx-only.

## Polyglot support

moon runs anything on PATH without requiring Node for non-JS lanes, and its v2 WASM toolchain system extends the project graph for JavaScript, Rust, and Go, with Python and Ruby unstable. For repositories where JS is one lane among Go or Rust services, that neutrality is a draw.

The Nx language plugins go deeper per ecosystem: [`@nx/gradle`](/docs/technologies/java/gradle/introduction) and the Maven and .NET plugins parse the build definitions themselves to discover projects, dependencies, and tasks, so the graph reflects actual code relationships rather than declared ones. Community plugins cover Python, Rust, and Go.

## Code generation and migrations

moon scaffolds files from Tera templates and can merge JSON/YAML. Nx generators are programmatic: they modify TypeScript ASTs, read the project graph, and compose, and the same machinery powers [`nx migrate`](/docs/features/automate-updating-dependencies), which updates your dependencies and transforms your configuration and code between versions automatically. moon has no update automation equivalent. Its migration extensions cover importing workspaces from Nx and Turborepo, not keeping your own tooling current.

## Module boundaries

moon enforces layer and tag relationship constraints declared in workspace config, language-agnostic and on by default. Nx [enforces boundaries](/docs/features/enforce-module-boundaries) at the import level for JS/TS by analyzing actual import statements through a lint rule, with [conformance rules](/docs/enterprise/conformance) extending enforcement to other languages.

## Ecosystem

moon is maintained by a two-person team as an MIT project, with an active release cadence and a small community. Its npm download counts are a small fraction of those for Nx, with the caveat that moon also installs through proto and Homebrew. There are no framework-level plugins, so React, Angular, or Storybook integration is yours to wire.

Nx ships [first-party plugins](/docs/plugin-registry) across frameworks and languages, [Nx Console](/docs/getting-started/editor-setup) for VS Code and JetBrains, and a full-time team behind both the CLI and Nx Cloud.

## Who should pick which

Nx fits when any of these apply:

- You want managed remote caching and CI distribution rather than services you run yourself.
- Your workspace is framework-heavy and benefits from plugins, generators, and automated migrations.
- You need e2e test splitting, flaky-task handling, or release management.

moon fits when any of these apply:

- You want pinned toolchains managed for you through proto.
- Your repository is polyglot with Go or Rust lanes that shouldn't need Node.
- Static CI sharding and a self-hosted remote cache are enough.

proto is worth a look even if you don't adopt moon, since Nx composes with it.

